# Jenkins + SonarCloud Pipeline — Troubleshooting Reference

Setup: Jenkins on a single EC2 box (Amazon Linux, ~1 GB RAM), declarative pipeline
running `mvn clean verify sonar:sonar` against SonarCloud for the `easybuggy` app.

Symptom that started it all: build stuck at **"Waiting for next available executor."**
Root cause was NOT slowness — the build was never running.

---

## 1. Build never scheduled — node was benched

The controller's built-in node was taken offline by node monitors, so no executor
was ever granted. Two monitor thresholds were tripping.

### a) No swap (Free Swap Space = 0 B)

~1 GB box with zero swap. Added a 2 GB swapfile:

```bash
sudo dd if=/dev/zero of=/swapfile bs=128M count=16
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
sudo swapon /swapfile
free -h                                              # confirm Swap: 2.0Gi
echo '/swapfile none swap sw 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab   # persist across reboot
```

### b) Free Temp Space below threshold (the real blocker)

`/tmp` was a 459 MB tmpfs — can never satisfy Jenkins' 1 GiB temp-space threshold,
so the node stayed offline permanently. Fix: point the JVM's temp dir at the root
volume (4+ GiB free) instead of the tiny tmpfs.

```bash
# create a temp dir on the real disk
sudo mkdir -p /var/lib/jenkins/tmp
sudo chown jenkins:jenkins /var/lib/jenkins/tmp
sudo chmod 700 /var/lib/jenkins/tmp
```

The RPM launches Jenkins via the `/usr/bin/jenkins` wrapper, which passes `JAVA_OPTS`
to java. Set it via a systemd drop-in override (written directly to avoid editor issues):

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/system/jenkins.service.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/jenkins.service.d/override.conf > /dev/null <<'EOF'
[Service]
Environment="JAVA_OPTS=-Djava.io.tmpdir=/var/lib/jenkins/tmp"
EOF

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
sleep 45
ps aux | grep '[j]ava' | grep -o 'java.io.tmpdir=[^ ]*'   # must print /var/lib/jenkins/tmp
```

Result: node came back online and stayed online. Build scheduled and ran.

### Useful diagnostics used along the way

```bash
df -h /                                              # disk usage (was fine at 48%)
free -h                                              # RAM + swap
sudo systemctl status jenkins --no-pager | head -8   # is Jenkins healthy
sudo journalctl -u jenkins --no-pager | tail -30     # check for OOM / errors
grep -i executor /var/lib/jenkins/config.xml         # numExecutors (was 2, fine)
cat /var/lib/jenkins/queue.xml                        # queued items + reasons
sudo cat /usr/bin/jenkins                             # confirm which var the wrapper reads
sudo systemctl cat jenkins                            # see ExecStart
# watch builds appear:
watch -n2 'sudo ls /var/lib/jenkins/jobs/ASGBuggyDevSecOpsPipeline/builds/'
# tail a build log live:
sudo tail -f /var/lib/jenkins/jobs/ASGBuggyDevSecOpsPipeline/builds/<n>/log
```

Quick-unblock alternative (if you'd rather not restart Jenkins) — lower the temp
threshold via Manage Jenkins -> Script Console:

```groovy
import hudson.node_monitors.*
hudson.node_monitors.TemporarySpaceMonitor.DESCRIPTOR.setFreeSpaceThreshold("256MiB")
println "threshold lowered"
```

